EvaluatedAnnotations.Reason: The annotation is not relevant because it refers to the storage time, which is not the same as the expected operating life.

EvaluatedAnnotations.Name: min. shelf life
EvaluatedAnnotations.Definition: time span how long a product can be stored without losing its typical qualities
EvaluatedAnnotations.Reason: The annotation is not relevant because it refers to the minimum shelf life, which is not the same as the expected operating life.

BestAnnotation.Name: product life (time)
BestAnnotation.Definition: period over which a system, subsystem, component or piping has been stored and used since production

GeneratedAnnotation.Name: expected product life (time)
GeneratedAnnotation.Definition: typical time period that a product can be used

Annotations.Affordance: The expected operating life can be used to determine the typical time period that the product can be used, and to plan for maintenance or replacement of the product.
